<TITLE> Kenya president urges calm, opposition sees anarchy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAIROBI, Jan 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Kenya's President Mwai Kibaki called for calm on Tuesday and opposition leader Raila Odinga warned that the east African nation was heading towards anarchy. "The president appeals to all Kenyans to maintain peace," said a statement from Kibaki's office. Odinga told reporters: "This country is drifting into a state of anarchy." At least seven people were killed with machetes and arrows during ethnic fighting in the Kibera slum of Kenya's capital Nairobi on Tuesday, a witness said. Military helicopters fired above a crowd terrorising refugees in the lakeside city of Naivas
